    <h1>About</h1>
    Letrud conducted a review to understand how the term "pseudoscience" is used and defined. They examined various published works to see if there is a consensus on what qualifies as pseudoscience. The study found that there is no clear agreement on the classification of pseudoscience cases. However, certain examples are frequently mentioned, suggesting that these are widely recognized as typical pseudoscience. This finding is important because it highlights the difficulty in clearly distinguishing pseudoscience from legitimate science. Understanding these patterns can help improve how we identify and address pseudoscientific claims in everyday life, ensuring that scientific integrity is maintained.
  </article>

  <article id="abstract-article-NCQMQGFB" class="abstract-article">
    <h1>Scientific abstract</h1>
    Definitions of ‘pseudoscience’ are required to heed the established usage of the definiendum by subsuming those cases that are generally considered to be pseudoscientific, and by excluding those that are considered sciences. In this paper I sample the published record to assess the consensus on pseudoscience case classifications. The review finds inconclusive evidence for an overall agreement. However, the frequent usage of a small number of pseudoscience-cases indicates that these are considered paradigms of pseudoscience. I briefly discuss some practical implications of these findings for the pseudoscience demarcation project.
  </article>
